# Literature Review

## Introduction

The advancement and proliferation of information systems among enterprises have led to an increased
understanding of cybersecurity. Cybersecurity practices encompass a set of techniques and procedures
aimed at protecting systems, networks, programs, and data from attacks, damage, or unauthorized access.
These practices vary and are applied differently to different types of enterprises. This literature review aims
to compare critical cybersecurity threats and practices in the context of cloud computing among micro,
small, and medium enterprises (MSMEs). By conducting a survey among 289 MSMEs in Australia, the
study conducted by Tehrani and Shirazi (2014) highlights significant differences in their cloud security
practices. The findings of this review contribute to the identification of knowledge gaps and suggest
potential future research directions in the field of cybersecurity in cloud computing among MSMEs.

## Factors Influencing Cloud Computing Adoption

Several factors have been identified as influencing the adoption of cloud computing by MSMEs. Tehrani
and Shirazi (2014) found that factors related to advantaging organizational capability influence the
adoption of cloud computing technology by MSMEs. Additionally, Senarathna et al. (2018) highlight that
IT resources and external pressure significantly influence cloud computing adoption in Malaysian SMEs.
Hassan et al. (2016) further support these findings by identifying IT resources and external pressure as
factors influencing cloud computing adoption in Malaysian SMEs.
In the context of Romanian SMEs, Dinc et al. (2019) found that factors such as competition and
government, ICT providers and firm departments, employees, managers, and technological factors play
a significant role in the choice of adopting cloud computing technology. Furthermore, Asiaei and Rahim
(2019) identify data security, technology readiness, top management support, competitive pressure, and
innovativeness as the most significant factors in predicting the adoption of cloud computing in Malaysian
SMEs. Raut et al. (2019) focus specifically on the manufacturing sector and find that factors such as
hardware scalability and standardization, cost, innovation, installation and upgradation, and quality of
service significantly influence cloud computing adoption among manufacturing MSMEs.

## Benefits of Cloud Computing for SMEs

Cloud computing offers various benefits for SMEs. Kumar et al. (2017) highlight the following advantages
of cloud computing for SMEs: cost advantage, easy deployment process, easier access to the latest
information and communication technologies, automatic updates and upgrades, scalability, flexibility, and
1 / 4
